<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Cement Entrepreneurs Say No to New Factory in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Local owners of cement
industries in Bangladesh Saturday suggested the government not to
allow any more new cement factory in the country, saying it will
destroy the local industry.
</P>
<P>
"At present, cement production is exceeding the demand. The
manufacturers are driven to unhealthy competition and the quality
of cement has been hampered," Ahmed Akbar Sobhan, president of the
Bangladesh Cement Manufacturers Association said at a press
conference Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, the president said many cement
industries would turn sick and their owners become bank loan
defaulters if new investments are allowed in this sector.
</P>
<P>
The statement said in the year 2002, the country's 62 cement
factories would produce 16 million metric tons of cement and
another 2 million tons will be imported, but the market demand
would remain at only 5.5 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The association predicted a sharp fall in cement price by 2002,
which would finally make the country's cement industries cripple.
</P>
<P>
They sought the intervention of the authorities to enable the
country's cement factories to survive, and urged the government to
discourage production in the sectors as they see a grim future
ahead due to excess production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
