<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Third Parliament Elections Since Civil War Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The second and final round of
the third parliament elections since Lebanon's civil war ended
Sunday evening after voters in Beirut, Bekaa and southern provinces
cast their ballot.
</P>
<P>
Polls closed at 6 p.m. (1500 GMT) when about 800,000 voters cast
their ballots. Some 1.4 million people of 2.5 million eligible
voters registered and got electoral cards.
</P>
<P>
The voters will choose 65 deputies from 259 candidates. In
Beirut, 19 deputies will be picked up. Twenty-three parliament
members will be chosen from the provinces of Bekaa Valley and South
each. The rest of the 128 parliament members have already been
chosen from the provinces of North and Mount in the first round
ballot last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
President Emile Lahoud urged the winners on Sunday to "work
together and save Lebanon from the current economic depression."
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Michel Murr said in a news conference Sunday
that the authority holds "a neutral position and democratic
freedom" in the election process and the ministry has not received
any report about security problems in the three provinces. At least
22,000 troops and policemen were positioned in and around the poll
stations.
</P>
<P>
There is also no complaint about the work of preparation and
logistics, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The final result will be announced after two or three days.
</P>
<P>
The focal point of Sunday's elections remained in Beirut, where
former Prime Minister Rafik al-Hariri waged battles against
reigning Prime Minister Salim Hoss and conservative deputy Tammam
Salam.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of the Beirut battle will have a crucial bearing on
the makeup of the post-election government, local political
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The Amal Movement, headed by Speaker Nabih Berri, made alliance
with Hezbollah in south Lebanon, where elections was held for the
first time since Israel's occupation in 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
