<HEADLINE> Somali President Calls for Arab Assistance to Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Somalia's new president,
Abdiqasim Salad Hassan, on Sunday called on the Arab states to
provide assistance to his country's reconstruction process.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the opening ceremony of the two-day 114th Arab
League Foreign Ministers Council, Salad said Somalia is facing
formidable tasks, starting with rebuilding the infrastructures,
ravaged during the long-standing civil war.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of reconstruction process for not
only Somalia itself but also the whole Arab world as the collapse
of the Somali state had caused "a dangerous security vacuum" in the
Arab region.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has been in anarchy since 1991 when former president
Mohammed Siad Barre was toppled. A reconciliation conference hosted
by Djibouti formed a transitional parliament on August 13, which
elected Salad to the presidency on August 25. Both the parliament
and the president are the first in a decade in the Horn of Africa
country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters later, Salad said his top priority is to
create a government by first appointing a prime minister.
</P>
<P>
After that, the government will start collecting weapons from
the numerous militia groups, he said.
</P>
<P>
Salad, who arrived here Saturday on his first international tour
since his election, will move on from Cairo to New York Tuesday to
attend the United Nations General Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
