<HEADLINE> French Firm Contracted to Keep Alexandria Clean Over 15 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Alexandria signed on Sunday with
Onyx, an offshoot of French conglomerate Vivendi, a contract worth
500 million euro (450 million U.S. dollars) to keep the Egyptian
Mediterranean city clean over the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The deal to handle 1 million tons of garbage a year produced
by the city of 3.5 million residents was a departure from
traditional methods, Henri Troglio, the boss of Onyx's parent,
Vivendi Environnement, said after he inked the contract with
Alexandria Governor Mohamed Abdel Salam al Mahgoub, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Onyx will collect household, business, medical and non-toxic
industrial waste, clean urban areas and beaches, operate three
sorting and disposal plants, close three tips and open a new one,
and build and operate an incinerator.
</P>
<P>
Company heads said the contract, one of the largest signed by
Onyx in terms of the population to be served, was an important step
in developing Vivendi Environnement's activities in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
The group also specializes in water management, energy and
transport.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Prime Minister Atef Obeid, who attended the signing
ceremony, said that negotiations are underway with environment
firms to clean cities in 11 of Egypt's 26 governorates.
</P>
<P>
Some of the contracts are expected to be signed by the end of
the year, Obeid added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
