<HEADLINE> Iraq Refutes Iranian Allegations Over Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq rejects all the
allegations made by Iran over the recent riots in an Iranian city,
an Iraqi foreign ministry said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the spokesman said it is proofless for Iran to
claim that Iraq was behind the riots in the western city of
Khoramabad, capital of Iran's Lorestan Province.
</P>
<P>
The riots, which broke out on August 26 after two leading
intellectuals were blocked from entering the city to address a
nationwide conference, have left one policeman dead and many others
injured. The riots touched off days of violence between supporters
of the pro-reform group and Iran's conservative radicals.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has nothing to do with the unrest, which is completely
Iran's internal affairs, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Iranian authorities have issued a decree to probe the unrest and
reveal the "behind-the-scene factors" in the violent incident.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman accused Iran of supporting Iraq's
opposition groups both "politically and financially."
</P>
<P>
For years, Iraq and Iran have been trading accusations for
harboring each other's opposition groups engaged in terrorist
activities. The dispute has been a major obstacle to the
normalization of bilateral ties, which remain tense more than 10
years after the 1980-1988 bloody war.
</P>
<P>
The war ended with a United Nations-brokered ceasefire in 1988,
but the two neighbors have never signed a peace treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000903.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Want Implementation of Signed Agreements: Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
said here Sunday that the Palestinian side did not ask the
impossible from Israel but only the proper implementation of all
signed agreements between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remark in response to the urge of Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak that the Palestinians should show flexibility
in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was speaking after his return form the Egyptian capital
of Cairo, where he took part in the Arab League foreign ministers'
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Terming the meeting as significant, Arafat said the Arab foreign
ministers supported the Palestinian rights.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Arab foreign ministers' meeting early on Sunday,
Arafat said there would be no peace without the declaration of an
independent Palestinian state with East Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who is going to New York to take part in the United
Nations Millennium Summit, said his government would not accept any
peace step unless Arafat showed more flexibility.
</P>
<P>
United States President Bill Clinton is expected to meet Barak
and Arafat, who is also going to attend the U.N. event, separately
in New York on September 6 on the sidelines of the U.N. summit in
another bid to reach an Israeli-Palestinian peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the gap is still wide between the two parties on the final-
status issues, particularly the status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. suggestion to share control over Old Jerusalem was turned
down by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Maguid said, "The holy
city of Jerusalem is a Palestinian Arab, Muslim and Christian city
and the heart of the Arab-Israeli conflict. Control over Jerusalem
should not be shared by the Palestinians and Israel."
</P>
<P>
It was also announced during the meeting that an Arab summit
will be held in Cairo early 2001. This summit will be the first of
its kind since 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
