<HEADLINE> U.S.-Palestinian Summit Crucial for Peace Process: Arafat's Adviser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's
adviser Nabil Abu-Rudienah described here on Sunday the coming
summit between Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton, to be held
on September 6 on the sidelines of the United Nations Millennium
Summit, as decisive for the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting will be an important occasion for reviewing the
overall situation and a crucial turning point to either
constructive ideas on the peace process or the whirlwind of the new
negative Israeli policy that could be imposed on the region," Abu-
Rudienah told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians urge for a more effective U.S. role and a more
serious Israeli attitude towards the peace talks, he said.
</P>
<P>
The coming few days will test Israel's seriousness and the
effectiveness of the United States administration in pressuring
Israel to respect the signed accords, he added.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will address the opening session of the millennium summit
to identify the guidelines of the Palestinian position on Mideast
peace in the coming period and assert the Palestinians' right to
declare statehood, Abu-Rudienah said.
</P>
<P>
Abu-Rudienah said Arafat will also meet a score of world leaders
in New York, including Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese
President Jiang Zemin, on the sidelines of the U.N. summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
