<DOCNO> XIE20000903.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Tired, old looking and worn and faded textiles appear
to be popular nowadays in the European carpet market.
</P>
<P>
This trend is a stark contrast to the medieval, 16th to 19th
century European taste for genuine, brightly colored and patterned
Islamic woven textiles.
</P>
<P>
As bright, spirited colors are no longer required for the
European market and carpets are usually woven in bright colors,
they pose a selling problem.
</P>
<P>
Such a phenomenon is a reflection of the tiredness, loss of
innocence, of vitality and of the barrenness of European taste
although there are other possible explanations.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Majlis (parliament) passed a bill on Sunday to
exempt non-oil exports from duties.
</P>
<P>
The bill is intended to remedy the country's floundering economy
and over-dependence on volatile oil income.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago the Majlis also passed almost unanimously a draft
bill that would encourage as well as protect foreign investment,
desperately sought by the country as a key to raising production
and solving unemployment.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey has increased its exports to Russia by 15
percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Union of Chambers and Commodities Exchanges and the
Exporters Council plan to set up a "Turkish Trade Center" in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Russian and Turkish businessmen met over the weekend at the
Chamber of Commerce in Izmir, southwestern Turkey, to discuss ways
to promote the bilateral trade ties.
</P>
<P>
Russian officials said Russia holds interest in Turkish leather,
metal and food sectors, and that they expect the trade volume
between Russia and Turkey to reach 3.3 billion U.S. dollars this
year.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish import of crude oil reduced by 3 percent
in 1999 to 22.9 million tons from 23.7 million tons in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total imports last year, 4.77 million tons of oil
were imported from Iraq, 4.75 million from Iran and 3.6 million
from Libya.
</P>
<P>
The costs of oil imports increased by 34.2 percent from 2.4
billion dollars to 2.7 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
The domestic production of crude oil dropped to 2.9 million tons
in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
