<DOCNO> XIE20000903.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Omani Minister Terms Peace With Israel as Arab Strategic Option </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Omani Minister of State for
Foreign Affairs Yousef Bin Alawi Bin Abdullah said Sunday that
Arabs have chosen "just and comprehensive" peace with Israel as a
strategic option.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the inaugural session of the Arab League
Foreign Ministers Council, Bin Alawi stressed that such a peace
should lead to the establishment of an independent Palestinian
state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The peace should also secure the return of the Golan Heights
that Israel seized from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War through the
implementation of U.N. Security Council resolutions 242 and 338, he
said.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day session, the Arab foreign ministers will
focus their discussions on the Middle East peace process,
especially the issue of Jerusalem, which lies at the heart of the
Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Peace will not be guaranteed in the Middle East if Israel has
full control over Jerusalem and the Palestinian national right to
East Jerusalem which was also occupied by Israel in the 1967
Mideast war are not secured, the Omani official said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want East Jerusalem as the capital of their
future independent state.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the Mideast peace process and Jerusalem, the Arab
ministers are also due to discuss other issues related to the Arab
world, including international trade sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries must work to end the tragedy suffered by Iraq and
its people as soon as possible, Bin Alawi told his Arab
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the "deep wounds" caused by Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait, Arab countries still "have the responsibility" to exert
efforts to find a solution to the "tragic situation" of the Iraqi
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
He described the Iraqi crisis as "an Arab-Arab crisis," which "
the U.N. Security Council has been unable to solve."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. economic sanctions since its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
