<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Ministers of Trade, Transport to Visit Iraq on Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior Jordanian delegation
headed by Minister of Trade and Industry Wasif Azar is expected to
visit Iraq on Monday to discuss ways of boosting trade ties between

the two countries, Jordanian officials announced on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Azar and his delegation, which also includes Minister of
Transport Mohammad Kalaldeh, will meet Iraqi Minister of Trade
Mohammad Mehdi Salah and other senior Iraqi officials during the
four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Iraq, the most important trade partner of Jordan,
has exported to Jordan various products valued at some 206 million
U.S. dollars in the first half of this year, which accounted for 67
percent of Jordan's total imports, said Jordan's official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, the only source of crude oil for Jordan, provides the
kingdom with 50,000 to 750,000 barrels per day at a preference
price
of 19 dollars per barrel, which is much lower than the
international market prices.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been trying to strike a diplomatic balance between
Iraq and Iraq's arch Arab foes Kuwait during the 1990 Gulf crisis,
which was triggered by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Jordan had been isolated by Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and other
Arab countries for its sympathy with Iraq during the Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming Jordan-Iraq talks in Baghdad will also cover Iraq's
imports via Jordan's red sea harbor Aqaba, which declined
drastically during the first seven months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, which used to import most of its commodities through
Aqaba, imported only 28,482 tons in the first seventh months of
this year compared to 6.8 million tons in 1998, Jordanian officials
said. Baghdad is reportedly unhappy with a lack of support for
the
Iraqi government from Amman despite Jordan's constant calls for an
end to the sufferings of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two Arab neighbors have witnessed a major
improvement since the July visit to Amman by Iraqi Vice President
Taha Yassin Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein held talks with Ramadan. It
was the first time for him to to meet a senior Iraqi official since
he assumed the throne in February last year.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Prime Minister Ali Abu Ragheb, who took office on June
19, has pledged to forge closer ties with Iraq and help end the U.
N. sanctions imposed on Baghdad since its invasion of Kuwait in
1990.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
