<HEADLINE> Iranian Parliamentarians Propose Amnesty to Political Exiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 40 Iranian Majlis
(parliament) members on Sunday proposed a draft bill to grant
amnesty to those who escaped from the country because of their
affiliations to outlawed political parties.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft, all exiled members of outlawed political
groups would be granted amnesty except for those who took up arms
and conduct terrorist operations against Iran, the Islamic Republic
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Proponents of the draft said they sponsored the amnesty to mark
the Imam Ali Year, designated by supreme leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei in the advent of the current Iranian year, 1379 (started
March 2000).
</P>
<P>
They urged the Majlis to pass the bill and enforce the law not
later than the end of the current Iranian year. But the report did
not say when the bill is to be discussed in the Majlis.
</P>
<P>
The amnesty will certainly exclude members of the Iraq-based
Iranian military opposition Mujaheddin Khalq Organization (MKO),
which was outlawed in 1981.
</P>
<P>
Labeled by Iran as a "terrorist group," the MKO has launched
numerous cross-border attacks inside Iran in recent years,
including assassinating senior Iranian officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
