<HEADLINE> Fuel Crisis Worsens in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 3 (Xinhua) -- An acute shortage of fuel
persists in Zimbabwe despite the government assurances that the
problem will end soon.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has been facing shortages of petrol, diesel and
paraffin since November last year, largely due to the shortage of
foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
A survey by the Zimbabwe News Agency on Sunday showed the most
service stations in Harare, the country's capital, were dry.
</P>
<P>
In Bulawayo, the second largest city in Zimbabwe, service
stations completely ran out of petrol and diesel supplies on
Sunday, as the fuel crisis in the city continued to worsen, the
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"I have been sleeping in the queue since Friday, but nothing
has come yet," one motorist queuing in the city center told the
agency.
</P>
<P>
"How can they increase the price of fuel by over 40 percent,
yet the commodity is not available. Something is terribly wrong
with our government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although the National Oil Company of Zimbabwe increased the
price of fuel by 41 to 101 percent with effect from Thursday night,
the commodity is still unavailable on the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
