<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: U.N. Summit to Hammer Out Strategies to Meet Challenges in New Century (by Gu Zhenqiu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is
scheduled to open the Millennium Summit here Wednesday in what
will turn out to be a historic occasion for the 188 member states
to address the challenges of the new century.
</P>
<P>
Momentum is building for the three-day event, which is expected
to be the largest-ever gathering of heads of state or government
in the history of the world body, with more than 150 heads of
state or government indicating their intentions to take part in
the September 6-8 forum to focus on the role of the United Nations
in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said that it is essential
that the Millennium Summit should provide an opportunity for a "
moral commitment" to the principles of the U.N. Charter and new
political momentum for global cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who has promoted the meeting as the most important in
the 55 years since the establishment of the United Nations, said
in his report, "The new millennium, and the Millennium Summit,
offer the world's peoples a unique occasion to reflect on their
common destiny, at a moment when they find themselves
interconnected as never before."
</P>
<P>
The summit will be convened in the face of the complex and
volatile international situation, and the world has witnessed the
disgraceful hostage-taking of U.N. peacekeepers by Sierra Leonean
rebels, the marginalization of the United Nations in the
maintenance of world peace and security, and the "human rights
over sovereignty" and "neo-interventionist" fallacies.
</P>
<P>
The decision to hold the summit stems from the conviction that
the turn of the century presents "a unique and symbolically
compelling moment to articulate and affirm an animating vision for
the United Nations in the new era," in words of the December 1998
resolution of the United Nations General Assembly, which
designated its 55th session as the Millennium Assembly, with the
Millennium Summit taking place at its outset.
</P>
<P>
In addition to making formal speeches at the summit, the heads
of state or government will have the opportunity to participate in
one of four interactive round tables, each to be chaired by a head
of state or government nominated from a different region.
</P>
<P>
Heads of state or government have also been invited by Annan to
take the opportunity of the summit to sign or deposit instruments
of ratification for multilateral treaties they may not yet have
joined, especially 25 core treaties representing key U.N.
objectives. Those treaties range from human rights, as well as
civil and political rights to the destruction of anti-personnel
landmines.
</P>
<P>
Under the summit's overarching theme of "the Role of the United
Nations in the 21st Century," member states have agreed to discuss
four specific themes during the three-day summit: poverty and
development, conflict prevention, environmental problems, and
strengthening the role of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, world leaders are also expected to focus their
attention on the reform of the U.N. and the Security Council, the
negative impact of globalization on the developing world, the
upholding of the Security Council authority in the maintenance of
international peace and security, U.N. back dues, HIV/AIDS, U.N.
peacekeeping operations, the information technology, disarmament
and human rights.
</P>
<P>
All these problems are posing grave challenges to the United
Nations, which, under the charter, has the primary responsibility
for the maintenance of international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The Millennium Summit will be the first summit to be attended
by the leaders of all U.N. member countries since October 1995,
when the international organization held a special meeting to
celebrate the 50th anniversary of its establishment.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has unanimously chosen the presidents of
Namibia and Finland to be the joint chairmen of the upcoming
Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
Heads of state or government of the 15 members of the Security
Council, will hold a summit on September 7 to discuss the U.N.
peacekeeping operations in the world, in Africa in particular. The
council has met only once at summit level, on January 31, 1992, a
few weeks after the collapse of the Soviet Union and the end of
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, founded in 1945 after World War II by 50
countries for the purpose of saving "succeeding generations from
the scourge of war," has neither achieved nor been equipped for
attaining that high ideal.
</P>
<P>
With 188 members, the United Nations is overwhelmed by demands
and crises, and has undergone numerous reforms. The declaration
the heads of state or government will adopt on September 8 points
to various areas that have made world headlines: globalization,
management of the world economy, peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The declaration deals with basic human freedoms: freedom to
live and raise children in dignity, and freedom from hunger, from
fear and violence, oppression or injustice. It calls for equality
among nations and individuals, tolerance and respect for nature.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state or government are also expected to hammer
out strategies to carry out programs by specific target dates: the
halving by 2015 the current 22 percent of the world's population
living on less than one U.S. dollar a day; halving the current 20
percent of people without drinking water; and giving equal access
to boys and girls to all levels of education. By 2020, programs to
improve the lives of 100 million slum dwellers should be
implemented in developing and transitional countries.
</P>
<P>
The world, the developing nations in particular, always turns
its eyes to the United Nations at the time of crisis and for the
establishment of a fair and just international political and
economic order, but the world body is currently deep in the
financial crisis largely due to the U.S. reluctance to pay its
back dues in full, on time and without any condition.
</P>
<P>
In fact, however ambitious a program is, the non-profit-making
United Nations, as always, needs unequivocal political will and
generous financial support from member states, especially the rich
Western countries, to carry out what has been agreed upon by the
international community. Otherwise, the most universal body will
simply let the world community down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000903.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Olympic Team Bound for Sydney with High Hopes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The South African Olympic
team will leave for Sydney on Sunday night with high hopes of
bettering the nation's medal tally of five from the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"We are hoping for eight medals, anything else will be a bonus
for us," enthused President of the National Olympic Committee of
South Africa (NOCSA) Sam Ramsamy before the team's departure.
</P>
<P>
In response to the president's comment, the South African
Olympic squad's upbeat mood seemed to grant Ramsamy his wish.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 athletes, out of a total squad of 129, on Saturday
night gathered at the squad's holding camp at Esselen Park outside
Johannesburg to take care of last-minute arrangements and the
atmosphere was electric.
</P>
<P>
According to Ramsamy, South Africa's medal winners four years
ago at Atlanta Olympic Games were Penny Heyns, Josia Thugwane,
HezekielSepeng and Marianne Kriel.
</P>
<P>
However, Kriel, who won bronze in the backstroke, has now
retired.
</P>
<P>
It will be remembered that Heyns won gold in the 100m and 200m
breaststroke, setting world records in the process; Sepeng became
South Africa's first Black Olympic medalist when finishing a close
second in the 800m track event; and Thugwane won the closest
Olympic marathon in history to become the nation's first non-White
gold medalist.
</P>
<P>
But what prospects do the Millenium Olympics in Sydney from
September 15 to October 1 hold for the Rainbow Nation?
</P>
<P>
Firstly, the likely medal contenders are Heyns in both the 100m
and 200m breaststroke; Brendon Dedekind in the 50m freestyle;
RykNeethling in the distance freestyle; Llewellyn Herbert in the
400m hurdles; Sepeng in the 800m track event; Hestrie Cloete in
the women's high jump; the men's 400m track relay team and Frantz
Kruger in discus.
</P>
<P>
Then the fringe contenders are Elana Meyer, the 10,000m silver
medalist at the 1992 Barcelona Olympics; Thugwane and Colleen de
Reackin the marathon; the under-23 soccer tournament; the women's
hockey team, ranked sixth in the world; the tennis team, where the
best hopes lie with the world's fifth-ranked men's doubles
combination of David Adams and John laffnie de Jager; and rowing,
where women's light-weight pair appear the best equipped to reach
a final.
</P>
<P>
But then there is also the omnipresent pressure of the Olympic
Games, injury, illness, stage-fright and the plain old bad day at
the office to contend with.
</P>
<P>
Realistically then, anything more than five medals will be a
bonus for the South African Olympic squad.
</P>
<P>
As someone once said, competing at the Olympics is not all
about winning, but the joy of taking part, going faster, further
or higher than ever before will be a triumph in itself for most of
the South Africans in Sydney. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
