<HEADLINE> Egypt Court Again Postpones Verdict on Brotherhood Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's High Military Court on
Sunday deferred for the second time the announcement of sentences
on 20 Muslim Brotherhood members charged with reactivating the
banned movement.
</P>
<P>
The court at the Huckstep military base, 30 kilometers north of
Cairo, was due to pass verdict on Sunday but postponed the hearings
until November 7 without giving reasons, the country's Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The defendants, including two university professors and a former
legislator, have been in jail since their arrest last October which
marked the biggest crackdown on the Muslim Brotherhood in four
years.
</P>
<P>
They are accused of damaging social peace, belonging to an
illegal organization, trying to gain control of professional
unions, obstructing the constitution and instigating anti-
government propaganda.
</P>
<P>
The trial began on December 25 and a verdict had been expected
July 30 before the first deferral.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim Brotherhood was banned in the 1950s, but is partly
tolerated by the government, as it says publicly it is seeking to
establish an Islamic state through peaceful means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
