<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former President Files Writ Against Scrapping of Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi former President and
Jatiya Party Chairman H.M. Ershad Sunday filed a writ petition
with the High Court, challenging a notification of the Parliament
Secretariat which vacated his parliament membership following
conviction in a corruption case.
</P>
<P>
The writ petition that challenged the notification for
cancellation of Ershad's parliament membership, was issued on
August 30 under the signature of Mohammad Muktadir Chowdhury,
additional secretary of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
In his petition, Ershad termed the cancellation of his
parliament membership as illegal, saying nobody has the right to
cancel his parliament membership.
</P>
<P>
The writ petition challenged the authority of issuing the
notification which was signed by the additional secretary of the
parliament, who is not permitted by the law to issue such sort of
notification while the speaker was outside the country.
</P>
<P>
Further contention of the writ petition is that the issue of
notification of canceling Ershad's parliament membership is in
violation of the provision of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
It was also contended in the petition that there had been a
serious violation of Ershad's fundamental right on the question of
principles of natural justice without hearing Ershad or notifying
him before declaration of the cancellation of his parliament
membership.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament Secretariat on August 30 canceled the parliament
membership of Ershad as the High Court, upholding the verdict of a
lower court with certain modifications, sentenced the former
president to five years' imprisonment on a corruption Case.
</P>
<P>
"As per Article 66 (2) of the Constitution, Ershad is no longer
qualified to remain a member of Parliament following his
conviction by the High Court," the notification said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
