<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli PM Briefs Cabinet on His Forthcoming U.S. Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak Sunday briefed his ministers on his expected trip to the U.S.
for the United Nations' millennium summit, saying that he saw no
sign of flexibility from the Palestinian side ahead of his trip.
</P>
<P>
At Sunday morning's weekly cabinet meeting, Barak said that
during the summit due to take place on September 6-8, he will meet
more than 30 world leaders, including United States President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will also meet Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who is
also scheduled to fly to New York for the summit. These meetings
are widely regarded as the last chance to revive the Israeli-
Palestinian talks.
</P>
<P>
The two-way meetings are the first since July's Camp David
talks, which failed to reach any Israeli-Palestinian agreement due
to significant gaps between the two sides over the fate of
Jerusalem and the return of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Barak said Sunday that during the upcoming week he will see if
the Palestinians are receptive to the ideas raised by Clinton at
the Camp David summit and/or similar ideas which have been raised
recently by other countries, according to a statement issued by
Barak's office.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed that up until now he has not seen
any sign of flexibility or openness on the Palestinians' part that
could indicate the possibility of resuming the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He added that he is now waiting for a decision by Arafat and it
would not be correct on Israel's part to do anything at this stage
but wait.
</P>
<P>
Barak reiterated that neither a three-way meeting similar to the
Camp David summit, between him, Arafat and Clinton, nor a two-way
meeting with Arafat has been set so far.
</P>
<P>
Barak's office had denied such rumors several times in the past
few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
