<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Agrees to Dismantle Religious Affairs Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli cabinet Sunday
morning unanimously agreed to dismantle the Religious Affairs
Ministry, a move that may infuriate the religious society.
</P>
<P>
At the weekly cabinet meeting, cabinet ministers approved Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's decision to disband the ministry as part of
his civil reform plan.
</P>
<P>
The plan was unveiled by Barak two weeks ago, in which he
promised to deliver a constitution within a year, approve civil
marriages, call for national military service for all and cancel
the Ministry of Religious Affairs.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, the ministry's current departments will
be transferred to other ministries and local authorities.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed to set up a ministerial committee to be
headed by Religious Affairs and Justice Minister Yossi Beilin,
which will handle the actual issue.
</P>
<P>
Beilin recently charged that the ministry, which was under the
control of the ultra-Orthodox religious Shas party before its
resignation from the government this July, had been plagued by
political favoritism and cronyism.
</P>
<P>
It is still not clear whether or not Israel's religious society
will react harshly to Barak's plan, as the issue may fuel the
flames between the secular and religious Israelis, who had
developed more and more strain relations in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
But it was widely believed that the move will further reduce
Shas's chances to return to the coalition.
</P>
<P>
The party, which holds pivotal 17 seats in Israel's 120-member
Knesset (Parliament), was needed by Barak to restore his
parliamentary majority. Barak's coalition now controls only one
third of the Knesset seats.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel Radio Sunday quoted Beilin as saying that there
was no connection between the decision of dismantling the ministry
and the developments connected with Shas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
