<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China to Build 310 Geoparks
</P>
<P>
China is planning to build 310 geological parks in the next 10
years to protect its natural sites, and try to put five to eight
of the geoparks into the world geo-heritage list.
</P>
<P>
To fulfill these goals, China has recently set up the Geopark
Protection Office and the Geopark Evaluation Committee.
</P>
<P>
China Ends Ozone Research on Tibetan Plateau
</P>
<P>
China has completed the first systematic research on ozone and
ultraviolet radiation on the Tibetan Plateau.
</P>
<P>
The research was jointly conducted by the Tibetan Institute of
Plateau Atmosphere Environment and the Belgern University of
Norway.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou Technology Exhibition Opens
</P>
<P>
An exhibition on technical items for import and export opened
on August 28 in Guangzhou, capital city of south China's Guangdong
Province.
</P>
<P>
Over 70 Chinese and overseas companies have brought to the
three-day exhibition their latest technologies for trading at the
three-day event, covering the information industry, machine
building, bio-medicines, new environmental protection materials
and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
China Develops Routing Switch Technology
</P>
<P>
A Chinese company in Sichuan Province has made major
breakthroughs in developing routing switch products, the most
essential equipment in Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
Proved to be on par with international standards, this Chinese-
made products is expected to pose a challenge to the U.S.-based
Sisco which currently holds monopoly of China's routing switch
market.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao Sets Up Ocean Circumfluence Research Center
</P>
<P>
A joint research center on ocean circumfluence and climate
changes was recently set up in east China's coastal city of
Qingdao, the location of most China's oceanography research
institutes.
</P>
<P>
The research on ocean circumfluence has a lot to do with
changes in climate and ecological changes in the ocean, and has
significant meaning for the future of mankind, experts say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
