<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights
of major science stories released by Xinhua in the past week:
</P>
<P>
China Strives to Become Oceanic Giant
</P>
<P>
China is striving to become a modern oceanic giant in the 21st
century by developing its oceanic economy, marine science and
technology, while enhancing marine management and protection as
well as its overall marine strength.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Wang Shuguang, director of the State
Oceanic Administration, at a national maritime meeting which
opened on August 28.
</P>
<P>
China to Host Int'l Forum on Dissemination of Sciences
</P>
<P>
Over 100 noted Chinese and overseas writers specializing in
dissemination of kinds of science are expected to gather at a
Beijing forum between November 5 and 9 to exchange how to best
promote the awareness of sciences in the coming century.
</P>
<P>
Special Fund Established for Metallurgical Research
</P>
<P>
The Iron and Steel Joint Research Fund -- a national fund for
development of new metallurgical technology, new materials, energy,
and devices necessary for China's iron and steel industry growth
was established in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The 12-million-yuan (about 1.4 million U.S. dollars) special
fund was jointly established by the China National Natural Science
Foundation and the Shanghai-based Baoshan Iron and Steel Company.
</P>
<P>
China to Develop Oceanic Satellite
</P>
<P>
China will put its first oceanic satellite into orbit next year
after a series of weather and resources satellites have been
launched, said an official in the State Oceanic Administration (
SOA).
</P>
<P>
"The serial oceanic satellites will become China's major civil
satellites together with the Fengyun and Ziyuan series," Sun
Zhihui, deputy director of the SOA.
</P>
</TEXT>
