<DOCNO> XIE20000903.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Marks 100th Day After Lebanon Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak Sunday marked the 100th day since the Israel Defense Forces
withdrawal from south Lebanon in May.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before Sunday morning's cabinet weekly meeting, Barak
claimed that the withdrawal from the former Israeli-occupied
security zone in south Lebanon was his government's great
achievement.
</P>
<P>
"Thus we did when we brought the 18-year-long Lebanese tragedy
to an end. Thus we did when we got Israel out of its dangerous
diplomatic isolation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel launched a large-scale invasion against Lebanon in 1982
to drive out the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) based
there. And it set up a self-styled security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with a claimed aim to prevent terrorists from attacking
Israel's northern communities.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Barak's office quoted Barak as saying that
the past 100 days have given hope and opportunity for different
relations with Lebanon and Syria, which is the major foreign power
broker in Lebanon and had related its peace talks with Israel to
Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"For the past 100 nights, the parents of soldiers who served in
Lebanon have slept better. For 100 nights, we have not seen
helicopters flying the wounded to Ramban Hospital in Haifa," the
prime minister added.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese Muslim resistant groups, such as Hezbollah and
Amal, inflicted heavy Israeli casualties during the Israeli
occupation.
</P>
<P>
Barak said that the successful withdrawal, in which Israel
suffered no casualties at all and the border area between Israel
and Lebanon has been quiet since then, proved again that his
government could make difficult decisions and that it has not shied
away from them.
</P>
<P>
"This is a government whose responsibility is to lead and not to
be led, to initiate and not to sit on its hands and, mainly, to
promise and to carry out," he declared.
</P>
<P>
He promised that he will keep this way and do with the social-
civilian change in Israel, including the cancellation of the
Religious Affairs Ministry as part of his civil reform plan.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet will vote on Barak's decision on Sunday to disband
the ministry in a few weeks and transfer its departments to other
ministries and local authorities.
</P>
<P>
A ministerial committee headed by Religious Affairs and Justice
Minister Yossi Beilin will be formed to handle the issue. Beilin
recently charged that the ministry had been plagued by political
favoritism and cronyism.
</P>
<P>
It is still not clear whether or not Israel's religious society
will react harshly to Barak's plan. But it was widely believed that
the move will further reduce the ultra-Orthodox religious Shas
party's chances to return to the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Shas, which holds pivotal 17 seats in Israel's 120-member
Knesset (parliament) and controlled the ministry before its
resignation from the government in July, has condemned the move.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000903.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab FMs Open Meeting on Mideast Peace Process, Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League opened here on
Sunday the 114th meeting of its foreign ministers council to
discuss the Middle East peace process and rally support for the
Palestinians in their peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem will be the main subject of the two-day meeting of the
Arab foreign ministers, who will release a statement at the end of
the meeting, expressing support for Palestinian demand that East
Jerusalem be the capital of their future independent state.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem is an Arab, Palestinian and Islamic city that is the
core of the decades-old Arab-Israeli conflict, Arab League
Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid said in his opening address.
</P>
<P>
It is an Arab national right to recover East Jerusalem, which is
guaranteed by United Nations Security Council resolutions, Abdel-
Meguid said, stressing that there will be no bargaining or
concessions.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, who attended the meeting, was
also due to address the opening session. He was expected to brief
the participants on the latest developments of the peace talks with
Israel and call for unanimous Arab support for the Palestinian
people.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied East Jerusalem in the 1967 Mideast War and later
declared the whole of the holy city its "eternal and indivisible
capital," a claim the international community has never recognized.
The Arabs are insisting on Palestinian sovereignty over the eastern
sector of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the issue of Jerusalem and the Mideast peace
process, the Arab foreign ministers are also due to discuss a
proposal on convening regular Arab summits.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting Saturday night, the foreign ministers of Egypt,
Oman, Syria, Tunisia and Yemen, which formed a summit committee,
approved a mechanism for holding Arab summit in March every year.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the league's charter has made no provisions for
summits and considers the foreign ministers council the league's
highest body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
