<HEADLINE> S. African Hockey Team Excluded From Sydney Olympic Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- For South African
national field hockey captain Craig Jackson, the countdown to the
2000 Olympic Games in Sydney is a painful reminder of his dead
Olympic dream.
</P>
<P>
"We've put so much work into this sport and made a lot of
sacrifices," said Jackson, stressing: "Olympic competition is the
pinnacle for us. Now it's been taken away."
</P>
<P>
The National Olympic Committee of South Africa (NOCSA) earlier
this year excluded the predominantly white men's hockey squad, the
reigning African champions, from the Sydney Games, igniting an
explosion of protest that included debate in the South African
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, NOCSA still refused to yield. NOCSA President Sam
Ramsamy said the hockey squad does not have enough black players
to represent South Africa and can't erase doubts that the team
will improve on its 10th place finished at the 1996 Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
"This decision has more to do with politics and prejudice than
it does with merit. This has been a very sorry saga and a serious
setback for hockey in South Africa." said South African Hockey
Association President Clare Digby.
</P>
<P>
Digby said the team is probably expected to finish at least
ninth in Sydney, the NOCSA's standard for the team's going, since
it has done well against several countries in the 12-team Olympic
field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
