could determine both the fate of the peace process and his
government.
</P>
<P>
Officials in the Prime Minister's Office have said that if Barak
is able to reach an agreement, he will bring it back to the Knesset
(parliament) and breathe new life into his government. If he comes
back empty-handed, however, new elections appear almost certain.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Activists of Israeli ultra-Orthodox Shas Party preparing
demonstrations to accompany former Shas leader Aryeh Deri to prison
on Sunday have warned that the vicinity of the Ayalon Prison in
Ramle, near Tel Aviv, could see violent confrontations between the
protesters and police.
</P>
<P>
Deri has been ordered to present himself at the Ayalon Prison at
noon and is expected to arrive at the head of thousands of
supporters who leave from his home in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Deri was convicted of taking bribes and is sentenced to three
years in prison. He was ordered to begin his sentence on Sunday
after exhausting the appeals process.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak is to officially announce
Sunday that he will disband the Ministry of Religious Affairs as
part of his civil reform plan.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's office said Sunday night that Barak would
set up a ministerial committee headed by Justice Minister Yossi
Beilin, who has also been serving as acting religious affairs
minister.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- The United States has put a Patriot missile battery stationed
in Germany on alert for possible deployment to Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post reported that senior Pentagon officials said
the action stems from concerns that Iraq might try to fire missiles
at Israel during the U.S. elections in November.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak shrugged off any threat of
Iraqi missiles. He did, however, promise to be ready for the
possibility, no matter how remote it may be. 
</P>
