<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Not to Abolish Death Penalty: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will not abolish the
death penalty until it has achieved full national consensus on the
issue, the country's Legal Affairs Minister Vincent Malambo said
here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by Sunday Mail newspaper as saying that Zambia is
not party to the Second Optional Protocol on Civil and Political
Rights which obliges state parties to abolish the death penalty
for all crimes.
</P>
<P>
"Our position as government is that we will only accede to this
protocol when we have achieved full national consensus on the
abolition of the death penalty," he told the Catholic Commission
for Justice and Peace conference on the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
He said the death penalty in his country has a constitutional
basis and is in line with the International Convenant on Civil and
Political Rights which reserves the death penalty to only the most
serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a Lusaka lawyer appealed to the government to abolish
the death penalty because it is a cruel, inhuman and degrading
punishment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
