<HEADLINE> Second Round Voting in Lebanon's Parliamentary Elections Goes on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The second round of voting in
parliamentary elections started Sunday morning in seven
constituencies of Lebanon's three provinces -- Beirut, the Bekaa
Valley and the South.
</P>
<P>
Polls opened at 7:00 a.m. (0400 GMT). About 1.4 million voters
will choose 65 parliament members from 259 candidates, and decide
whether the opposition will consolidate its first round gains with
former Prime Minister Rafiq Hariri back to power.
</P>
<P>
In Beirut, 19 deputies will be picked up; and 23 deputies will
be chosen in each of the provinces of the Bekaa Valley and the
South.
</P>
<P>
The other members of the 128-seat parliament had been chosen
from the provinces of North and Mount in last Sunday's first round,
which saw opposition gains.
</P>
<P>
Elections are being held for the first time since 1972 in the
former Israeli-occupied south Lebanon. Israel withdrew its troops
from the border strip on May 24, after a 22-year occupation there.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry has deployed 22,000 troops to guard the
elections. A ministry source said Sunday morning that the process
went on orderly in all polling stations.
</P>
<P>
Television showed voters casting their ballots in procession and
officials said the results will be announced next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
