<HEADLINE> Jordanian Police Seize 2 Ancient Mummies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian police have recovered
two well-preserved ancient mummies from local treasure hunters from
the southern Karak district of the kingdom, police sources said on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two mummies, both females and about 3,700 years old, were
found by local treasure hunters in the Ghor Al Safi region of the
Karak district, 125 kilometers south of the capital city of Amman.
</P>
<P>
The would-be sellers were arrested by police upon a tip-off when
they tried to sell the mummies for 100,000 U.S. dollars to
potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian archaeologists believed the two, died at 16 and 26
years of age, were mummified with substances from the high-saline
Dead Sea which prevented the bodies from decomposing.
</P>
<P>
Further police investigations are under way into the mummy
smuggling effort. 
</P>
