<HEADLINE> U.S. Peace Envoy Returns Home without Major Achievements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Special Middle East
peace envoy Dennis Ross returned to Washington Saturday night after
winding up his two-week-long mediation between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Before departure, Ross held his last round talks with Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak, but no details of the talks had been
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Ross' mission to the region was to study the grounds for another
Camp David summit and persuade both Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat to soften their positions on key issues such as
Jerusalem so as to reach a peace accord on the Israeli-Palestinian
final-status talks soon.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides have come a long way...and obviously there are
still differences," Ross told reporters here Friday after meeting
with Barak.
</P>
<P>
Officials in the Prime Minister's Office continue to say that
Arafat has demonstrated no flexibility since the July Camp David
summit.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinian side says that Israel is the side that needs
to compromise on all the key issues, particularly the issue of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The 15-day marathon Camp David summit failed to reach a
framework agreement on final-status issues including Jerusalem,
borders, Palestinian refugees and Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
Ross returned to the region on August 17 and shuttled between
the two sides. He will report to Clinton on where the two sides
stand, before a decision can be made on whether or not to bring
Barak and Arafat together again soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
