<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sugar Shortage in Kenya Artificial: Authority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The current sugar shortage in
Kenya is artificial and the government would crack down on
unscrupulous traders who hoard the commodity thereby worsening the
crisis, the Kenya Sugar Authority (KSA) has said.
</P>
<P>
The People daily Sunday quoted KSA chief executive Francis
Chahonyo as saying that the government will withdraw licenses from
such traders and confiscate their hidden stocks for release into
the market.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has experienced a nationwide sugar shortage since last
month, which has driven the price up from 45 shillings (about 60 U.
S. cents) a kilogram to 80 shillings (about 1.04 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Mombasa, a port city in southeastern Kenya,
Chahonyo vowed to crush a powerful cartel lobbying for a sugar
duty waiver for cheap sugar imports at the expense of the Kenyan
farmers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
The government might be forced in the coming week to intervene
and stabilize market prices to avert a further shortage, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Agriculture Minister Chris Obure last Wednesday
attributed the sugar shortage to the El Nino weather phenomenon
which devastated the country's sugarcane-growing areas in 1998 and
the current prolonged drought. 
</P>
</TEXT>
