<HEADLINE> Mercosur, Andean Community to Start Integration Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of South
American Common Market (Mercosur) countries decided Friday to
negotiate with the Andean Community on establishing a free trade
zone between them by January of 2002.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports said Saturday that the decision was made in
the first South American summit that ended Friday in Brasilia
where the 12 presidents signed the a 59-point "Brasilia Communique.
"
</P>
<P>
The communique says that the presidents highlighted the
importance of markets liberalization in South America and welcomed
the negotiations. The leaders hoped to integrate the continents'
economies through a network of highways, bridges and river routes,
as well as telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian President Fernando Cardoso said that "integration is
a powerful instrument that will allow us to face the challenge of
globalization."
</P>
<P>
It believed that a continentwide trade bloc would give the
region greater bargaining power in the negotiations leading up to
the creation of the U.S.-sponsored Free Trade Area of the Americas,
scheduled to be in place by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, grouping Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay, Paraguay and
with Chile and Bolivia as associate members, and the Andean
Community, involving Venezuela, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru and
Bolivia, are the two main regional trade blocs in South America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
