<HEADLINE> Kayin Ethnic Armed Group Members Surrender in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-seven members of the
Kayin National Union (KNU), Myanmar's largest anti-government
ethnic armed group which has not made peace yet with the
government, surrendered to the government forces in late last
month, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 57 members, led by Pado Chit Po, "exchanged arms for peace"
in Tanintharyi township, southern Tanintharyi division, on August
26.
</P>
<P>
They brought along with them 17 assorted arms, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The KNU has been operating for over five decades since the
early days of Myanmar's independence. In early 1995, the KNU lost
their headquarters at Manerplaw and Kawmura on Myanmar-Thai border
during attack by its splinter group, the Democratic Kayin Buddhist
Army, backed by the government.
</P>
<P>
Again since December that year, four rounds of peace talks were
held between the government and the armed group but failed to
produce result.
</P>
<P>
According to official disclosure, up to now, 17 anti-government
ethnic armed groups as well as the Mong Tai Army, led by former
drug warlord Khun Sa, have made peace with the government with
cease-fire agreements reached between them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
