<P>
The daily quoted a policy source as saying that the increase is
likely to continue as more people use computers and hook onto the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
Between January and June, 127 computer crimes, including three
hacking cases, were reported, compared with 185 such cases for the
whole of last year which included 13 incidents of computer hacking,
the police source said.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, in 1997, however, there were only 39.
</P>
<P>
Using other people's email accounts and computer passwords
without their permission, made up the bulk of the cases so far
this year.
</P>
<P>
The Police attributed the increase to the rising capacity for
computer misuse and abuse as a result of increasing reliance of IT
as an efficient means of carrying out day-to-day activities.
</P>
<P>
If the six-month trend for the year continue, said the Police,
the number of computer crimes could hit 254 by year-end, or 38
percent more than last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000903.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Economic Growth Rate This Year to Be No Lower Than 4.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's economic growth
rate this year would not be lower than 4.1 percent, The Thai News
Agency (TNA) reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongkol Sonakul, the Governor of The Bank of Thailand (BOT)
, the country's central bank, was quoted as saying that Thailand's
economic growth rate this year would not be lower than 4.1 percent,
despite a current oil price hike.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed a recent projection of the Thailand Development
Research Institute (TDRI) that the Thai economy would grow no more
than 4.1 percent this year, citing strong exports that reached six
billion U.S. dollars in July, the highest monthly level in three
years, and continued U.S. economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices will not have a significant impact on the Thai
economy this year. Indeed, the psychological effect of a current
oil price hike is higher than its real effect on the country's
manufacturing sector, said the BOT chief.
</P>
<P>
Before the current oil price surge, the central bank and the
Finance Ministry forecast that the Thai economy would grow 4.5-5.5
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Finance Ministry reported that Thai exports,
based on a Customs Department report, in the first seven months of
this year reached 39 billion U.S. dollars, a 21.2 percent increase
from the same period of last year; while imports touched 34.07
billion U.S. dollars, an increase of 25 percent from the same
period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the January-to-July period, Thailand had a trade surplus,
based on the Customs Department figure, of 4.929 million U.S.
dollars, a slightly higher than that of 4.920 million U.S. dollars
in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Ministry's Department of Internal Trade also
forecast that the country's overall inflation this year would be
no more than 2.5 percent, as earlier targeted by the government,
though the consumer index in August rose by 0.6 percent from July'
s level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
