<HEADLINE> Alleged Arms Trafficking Ring Leaders Captured in Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A Peruvian and a Spaniard, two
alleged leaders of an arms trafficking ring that delivered
thousands of rifles to the Colombian guerrillas, were detained
here on Saturday, Peruvian National Police said.
</P>
<P>
Former Peruvian army lieutenant Luis Frank Aybar and Spanish
citizen Juan Manuel Lopez Rodriguez were arrested when they were
riding in a car driven by Jose Alejandro del Mar, also a Peruvian,
said the police in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Aybar and Lopez, who had tried to change their physical aspect
to dodge police investigation, have been detained in the Police
State Security Department, where they are being interrogated by
the special prosecutor in charge of the case, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Aybar and other members of the ring reportedly pretended to be
Peruvian army generals and in that guise bought 50,000 Russian-
made rifles from Jordan to deliver them to the guerrilla
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC).
</P>
<P>
The arms trafficking ring was uncovered by the Peruvian
information services after the presence of a Russian cargo plane
was detected in the Peruvian jungle, that supposedly had arrived
from Ukraine to buy two tons of compact wood.
</P>
<P>
It was established during the investigation that in 1999, the
Russian plane flew from Jordan with a cargo of 10,000 AK rifles
that were dropped with parachutes when the aircraft was flying
over Colombian territory controlled by the FARC.
</P>
<P>
The case was first unveiled by Peruvian President Albert
Fujimori in September 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
