<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Fiscal Reform Looks Beyond WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- As the Chinese government is
reforming its fiscal system to increase revenue and reduce
expenditure, experts here believe that the State treasury is
capable of making ends meet after the country's accession to the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Today's Business Weekly of China Daily quoted Liu Zuo, an
expert with the Taxation Science Research Institute under the
State Administration of Taxation, as saying this.
</P>
<P>
According to the Finance Minister Xiang Huaicheng, China will
reform the tax system in the coming years. Instead of taxing
production, China will target consumption in order to gradually
shift its value-added tax levy.
</P>
<P>
The country will adopt a unified income tax system for Chinese
and foreign-funded enterprises instead of its current preferential
policies, which aims to serve the government's goal of increasing
the amount of foreign capital of the country, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The anticipated tax reform is also expected to improve the
country's personal income tax system and adopt an inheritance tax
to narrow the gap between the rich and the poor.
</P>
<P>
China will be able to generate more tax revenue after its WTO
accession because the country's economy will develop faster and
people's income will rise, said Li Jingwen, an expert with the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
China's incorporation into the world economy will allow more
foreign companies to invest in the country, which means more
company and individual income taxes, Li said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000903.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Following are highlights of
major environment news stories Xinhua released from August 26 to
September 1:
</P>
<P>
China Implements Revised Air Pollution Prevention Law
</P>
<P>
China started to implement the revised Air Pollution Prevention
Law on September 1. According to the law, discharging pollutants
more than the state standards violates the law.
</P>
<P>
The law provides important regulations concerning the control
of coal burning, the ban of highly-polluting fuel in heavily-
polluted cities, and promotes the use of clean energy, said Xie
Zhenhua, director of the State Environmental Protection
Administration (SEPA).
</P>
<P>
He said regulations on the inspection of manufacturing,
repairing and fuel-burning of vehicles, quota management of the
production and import of products which can cause depletion of
ozone layer have also been added to the law.
</P>
<P>
Beijing to Hold Environmental Protection Exhibition
</P>
<P>
Beijing, the national capital, is to hold the Fifth China
International Environmental Protection Techniques and Equipment
Exhibition on September 11-14.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will display the development level and strength
of China's environmental protection techniques and equipment, and
help further international exchanges and cooperation in related
fields, explore new markets and promote the development of the
entire environmental protection industry.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 delegations and business people from a dozen
countries and regions including China, the European Union, Germany,
Spain, Austria, France, Sweden, the United States, Japan, the
Republic of Korea, and Singapore will take part in the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
China Publishes First Atlas on Population, Environment
</P>
<P>
China has published its first atlas on the country's population
and environment in both Chinese and English.
</P>
<P>
Containing 184 maps, over 200 photos and graphs, and 180,000
word descriptions, the atlas offers a large collection of data and
provides analyses of scientific research on the geographic
distribution of China's 1.2 billion population, and the situation
of their health and housing as well as consumption patterns.
</P>
<P>
Published by the Science Press, the atlas also contains
information on land, water, energy, forest, grassland and
biodiversity resources and situation of the country's environment,
including land degradation and water, air and noise pollution. (
more)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000903.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's First Nuclear Plant takes New Environmental Action
</P>
<P>
China's first built nuclear power plant has started to issue
regular environmental monitoring results.
</P>
<P>
According to the first report issued in mid-August by the
Qinshan nuclear power plant in east China's Zhejiang Province,
environmental condition during the second season of this year is
normal. The results will be published in a local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
More Sewage, Garbage Treatment Plants for Three Gorges Project
Area
</P>
<P>
Southwest China's Chongqing Municipality will build 10 sewage
treatment plants and 11 garbage treatment plants in its counties
around the Three Gorges Reservoir project area before 2003.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion, these areas will be able to treat 380,000 tons
of waste water and 2,800 tons of garbage daily, said an official
with the Chongqing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Reservoir will also be able to generate
electricity by 2003.
</P>
<P>
 Guiyang to Become Greener, Cleaner
</P>
<P>
Guiyang City, capital of southwest China's Guizhou Province,
plans to turn itself into a model city with more green land and a
cleaner environment.
</P>
<P>
According to city plans, greenery coverage in Guiyang is
expected to reach 40 percent in 2010, and per-capita public green
land will amount to 10 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The plan also requires that all new buildings must have an
afforestation rate of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
 40 Pollutant Power Plants Exposed
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Authorities have made public a list of the 40
polluting coal-burning power plants in efforts to press local
industries to pay greater attention to environmental issues,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The 40 coal-powered units exposed by the State Environmental
Protection Administration each discharges more than 5,000 tons of
dioxide annually.
</P>
<P>
Up to the end of this June, local environmental authorities
shut down a total of 4,732 high-sulfur coal mines, 778 small
cement and glass production lines, 404 small iron and steel mills,
and 1,422 big polluters in other industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000903.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Factories in Three Gorges Urged to Curb Pollution
</P>
<P>
The State Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA) has
urged factories in the Three Gorges area to bring pollution under
control as required.
</P>
<P>
So far, about half of the factories, either in operation or
under construction in this area, are not up to the state pollution
control standards, posing a threat to the quality of water in the
middle and upper reaches of the Yangtze River covered by the huge
reservoir at the Three Gorges, the SEPA said.
</P>
<P>
According to the SEPA, a project in the Three Gorges area must
curb pollution right from stage of designing, construction to
operation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Seaside Resort Combats Water Pollution
</P>
<P>
All of the polluted water in Beidaihe, one of China's most
famous summer resorts, has been disposed of and cleaned before
flowing into the sea, an official source said.
</P>
<P>
The quality of sea water there has been significantly improved
this summer and has met the requirements of the state's first-
class sea water standard, according to the local environment
monitoring center.
</P>
<P>
Last year the local government invested 120 million yuan (15
million U.S. dollars) on a sewage-disposal factory which started
operation earlier this summer. The government also launched a
drive to clean the rubbish so as to protect the ocean from being
polluted.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai to Recycle Sewage for Manufacturing Use
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is stepping up research of techniques in recycling
waste water for manufacturing use.
</P>
<P>
Within one year's time, it is expected that large quantities of
sewage and waste water produced by the city, estimated at 5.8
million cubic meters per day, together with abundant rainwater,
will become a major water source for washing vehicles, watering
plants, and irrigating farmland.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that with the new technique, the city's
pollution will be reduced and water resources will used more
efficiently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
