<HEADLINE> South Korean Makes Surprising Last Sixteen in U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Lee Hyung-Taik, who was
playing for his first major tennis tournament, surprised all by
reaching the round-of-16 at the U.S. Open here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 182nd-ranked Lee defeated German Rainer Schuttler 6-2, 3-6,
6-4 and 6-4, with his impending clash against four-time champion
Pete Sampras for a quarterfinal spot on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sampras never heard of Lee before this week, nor had he ever
heard of the guy he struggled against in the steamy heat on
Saturday, Argentina's Agustin Calleri, in a 7-6 (7-5), 7-6 (7-3),
6-3 win.
</P>
<P>
"I was told by someone in the locker room that he was a lefty
that stays back," Sampras said. "He was a righty that hits the
ball big. Bad information."
</P>
<P>
"He's going to come out swinging away, like the guy I played
today did," Sampras said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Galo Blanco of Spain knock off two-time champion
Patrick Rafter, and Arnaud Clement of France beat defending
champion Andre Agassi in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
No Korean man had ever gone beyond the first round in a major
tournament, making Lee, 24, not only a surprise here but a
celebrity in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
"He's the highest-ranked Korean player ever, so he's just
creating history in Korea when it comes to tennis," said Lee's
interpreter, Chris Kim of MBC, a Korean television network.
</P>
<P>
The tournament produced another string of upsets with Conchita
Martinez, Anna Kournikova, Yevgeny Kafelnikov and Mark
Philippoussis becoming the latest victims.
</P>
<P>
Kafelnikov, seeded No. 5, lost to Dominik Hrbaty 6-4, 7-6 (7-5),
6-1, and Jan-Michael Gambill upset the 15th-seeded Philippoussis 6-
4, 6-4, 6-4 in the
final second-round match postponed by rain Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Martinez, seeded seventh, lost to Elena Dementieva of Russia 6-
4, 6-1, and Justine Henin of Belgium ousted Kournikova, the No. 12
seed, 6-4, 7-6 (7-5).
</P>
<P>
In another men's match, ninth-seeded Lleyton Hewitt defeated
Jiri Novak of the Czech Republic 6-3, 6-3, 6-3. Also getting
through were No. 2 Lindsay Davenport, No. 4 Mary Pierce and No. 10
Anke Huber.
</P>
<P>
Davenport beat Tamarine Tanasugarn 6-2, 6-1, Pierce defeated
Lisa Raymond 6-4, 7-6 (7-6), Huber down Elena Likhovtseva 6-2, 6-3,
Lilia Osterloh beat Shinobu Asagoe 7-5, 6-0, and Jelena Dokic
stopped Francesca Schiavone 7-6 (4), 7-5. 
</P>
