<HEADLINE> UAE to Use European Food Safety Regulations for Reference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates'
General Secretariat of Municipalities (GSM) is consulting the
latest European Union white paper on food safety to modify the UAE
food safety specifications.
</P>
<P>
The white paper will be used as a base reference to boost the
emirates' own safety specifications, reported the official news
agency WAM on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The GSM, established in 1981, has been coordinating with UAE
municipalities to have a unified, standard safety code which will
include Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) food specifications, WAM
added.
</P>
<P>
According to a source from the GSM, other international food
safety specifications have always been studied during the period of
reviewing UAE standards.
</P>
<P>
The source said the GSM is now studying whether to add local
specifications according to GCC standards and other international
standards.
</P>
<P>
"The white paper is so useful because we know how one of the
biggest import and export unions for food products in the world is
drawing up legislation, keeping us abreast of what's happening and
it gives an opinion on what types of food are not fit for
consumption," added the source.
</P>
<P>
The EU white paper was issued in Brussels on January 12. The
paper deals with food and animal health, additives, flavouring and
packaging. 
</P>
</TEXT>
