<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, September 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- U.S. Special Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross
returned to Washington Saturday night after winding up his two-
week-long mediation between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Ross' mission to the region was to study the grounds for another
Camp David summit and persuade both Barak and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat to soften their positions on key issues such as
Jerusalem so as to reach a peace accord on the Israeli-Palestinian
final-status talks soon. (Israel-Ross-Mediation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Sunday marked the
100th day since the Israel Defense Forces withdrawal from south
Lebanon in May.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before Sunday morning's cabinet weekly meeting, Barak
claimed that the withdrawal from the former Israeli-occupied
security zone in south Lebanon was his government's great
achievement. (Israel-Lebanon-Withdrawal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli cabinet Sunday morning unanimously
agreed to dismantle the Religious Affairs Ministry, a move that may
infuriate the religious society.
</P>
<P>
The plan was unveiled by Barak two weeks ago, in which he
promised to deliver a constitution within a year, approve civil
marriages, call for national military service for all and cancel
the Ministry of Religious Affairs.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, the ministry's current departments will
be transferred to other ministries and local authorities. (Israel-
Religious Ministry)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat vowed on Sunday that
the Palestinian people will "continue to battle for sovereignty
over Jerusalem," making it the capital of their future independent
state.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem is "in danger" due to Israel's illegal practices to
judaize the holy city and its attempts to impose such solutions on
the Palestinians, which will fail to secure Palestinian national
rights, Arafat said while addressing the opening ceremony of the
114th session of the Arab League Foreign Ministerial Council here.
</P>
<P>
But "the Palestinian people who have long history of resistance
and uprising will carry on with the struggles to recover East
Jerusalem," he stressed. (Arab League-Palestine-Arafat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The second and final round of the third parliament
elections since Lebanon's civil war ended Sunday evening after
voters in Beirut, Bekaa and southern provinces cast their ballot.
</P>
<P>
Polls closed at 6 p.m. (1500 GMT) when about 800,000 voters cast
their ballots. Some 1.4 million people of 2.5 million eligible
voters registered and got electoral cards.
</P>
<P>
The voters will choose 65 deputies from 259 candidates.
(Lebanon-Election) 
</P>
