<HEADLINE> Nigerian Volunteers to Clean up Beaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- More than 5,000 volunteers in
Nigeria are to launch a campaign to clean up the country's beaches
so as to raise people's awareness on environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The volunteers, including students, government or non-
governmental employees, are expected to start the exercise on
September 16 on beaches in Nigeria's coastal cities like Lagos,
Port Harcourt.
</P>
<P>
They will remove millions of kilograms of pieces of debris and
rubbish carelessly or intentionally discarded on the beaches, and
collect data on the pollution sources.
</P>
<P>
Ene Bab-Owoh, chairman of Clean-up Nigeria, a non-governmental
organization and organizer of the exercise, said on Sunday here
that over the years, the ocean had become a dumping ground for
human garbage.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria needs the kind of awareness and efforts on
environmental protection in other parts of the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This year's exercise is expected to unite concerned volunteers
like school children, community leaders, governmental and non-
governmental organizations in solving the problem that is no
geographic, social or political boundaries," said Bab-Owoh.
</P>
