<HEADLINE> S. African Government Urged to Ban Plastic Bags </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 3 (Xinhua) -- South African
Environmental Affairs and Tourism Minister Valli Moosa said on
Sunday he hoped legislation would be introduced in Parliament
early next year to ban the general use of plastic bags in the
country once and for all.
</P>
<P>
The bags were the most visible symbol of a country which was
becoming dirtier by the day, especially in the poorer areas, he
told South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
He said he had received widespread support for the move when he
had announced it a year ago and government regulations on plastic
bags had already been issued.
</P>
<P>
Turning to tourism, Moosa said South Africa should not allow
itself to become paralyzed by a series of Cape Town bombings or
high crime levels.
</P>
<P>
Moosa said his department and tourist agencies were currently
embarking on the biggest-ever international marketing campaign to
attract more tourists for South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, Europe had yielded the most, but the United
States market had also grown and one of the biggest markets which
had now opened was Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moosa said most foreign tourists were now coming from this
continent.
</P>
<P>
South Africans also needed to be made more aware of what their
own country had to offer, Moosa said.
</P>
<P>
The government was doing all in its power to ensure that
opportunities were created for black South Africans to become more
involved in tourism service industries like hotels and restaurants.
</P>
