<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Euro Opposition Strong: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Over two-thirds of Britons
reject the entry of Europe's single currency, the euro, according
to an opinion poll published Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, carried out by independent pollsters ICM for the
Business for Sterling and the New Europe campaigns, showed 69
percent of Britons remain opposed to euro membership, with only 23
percent in favor and 8 percent saying they did not know.
</P>
<P>
The poll found that 58 percent of Labor voters opposed the euro,
while 84 percent of opposition Conservative voters were against it
as were 63 percent of Liberal Democrats. It also found 80 percent
of people in the 18-24 age group rejected entry.
</P>
<P>
The Labor government favors euro entry in principle and has
promised to make an assessment of the economic conditions early in
the next parliament and then hold a referendum if the economics
are right. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
